<p class="article-lead">Several scents cannot automatically be combined to meet one perfume MOQ. Each fragrance creates
    its own liquid batch, identification, filling changeover and artwork controls.</p>
<h2>What can sometimes be shared</h2>
<p>Plain bottles, pumps, caps and a common carton structure may be purchased across variants if the specifications are
    identical. Labels, printed scent names and fragrance liquid usually remain separate minimums.</p>
<h2>Ask four questions</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Is MOQ per fragrance, artwork, bottle design or total order?</li>
    <li>Which component has the highest supplier minimum?</li>
    <li>Will surplus packaging be stored or delivered?</li>
    <li>What changeover and inspection work is added?</li>
</ul>
<p>A smaller multi-scent launch is more practical with one bottle system and simple scent identification. The factory
    must review the actual split; combining quantities is an option, not a standard entitlement.</p>